        </div>

        <div id="locations" class="section">
            <h1>Prime Fishing Locations in Washington</h1>
            <h2>Eastern Washington</h2>
            <p><strong>Potholes Reservoir:</strong> Known for walleye, bass, and perch. The shallow flats and submerged dunes create perfect habitats for these species.</p>
            <p><strong>Banks Lake:</strong> Offers abundant bass, walleye, and rainbow trout fishing. Prime spots include the rocky points and submerged structure.</p>
            <p><strong>Columbia River:</strong> This vast river hosts salmon, sturgeon, and steelhead. Focus on tailouts below dams for excellent results.</p>

            <h2>Puget Sound</h2>
            <p><strong>North Sound:</strong> Ideal for targeting salmon in summer and fall. Popular areas include Everett and the San Juan Islands.</p>
            <p><strong>South Sound:</strong> Known for resident coho and cutthroat trout. Try Point Defiance or Gig Harbor.</p>

            <h2>Straits of Juan de Fuca</h2>
            <p>Offers prime halibut and lingcod fishing, especially near Sekiu and Neah Bay.</p>

            <h2>Coastal Waters</h2>
            <p><strong>Westport:</strong> A major salmon and bottomfish hotspot. The jetties and offshore banks provide excellent action.</p>
        </div>

        <div id="gear" class="section">
            <h1>Gear & Tactics</h1>
            <p><strong>Potholes Reservoir:</strong> Jigs and bottom bouncers work best for walleye. Use crankbaits or soft plastics for bass.</p>
            <p><strong>Banks Lake:</strong> Deep-diving crankbaits and live bait rigs excel in deeper water structures.</p>
            <p><strong>Puget Sound:</strong> Mooching with herring or trolling with flashers and spoons is effective for salmon.</p>
            <p><strong>Neah Bay / Straits:</strong> Heavy jigs and swimbaits are best for targeting lingcod and rockfish in rocky terrain.</p>
            <p><strong>Westport:</strong> Bottomfish anglers should use leadhead jigs or bait rigs tipped with squid for best results.</p>
        </div>

        <div id="info" class="section">
            <h1>Licenses & Fishing Information</h1>
            <p>Washington fishing licenses are required for anyone 15 or older. They can be purchased online via the Washington Department of Fish and Wildlife (WDFW) website.</p>
            <p><strong>Best Fishing Seasons:</strong> Salmon peaks in summer and fall, while trout and bass fishing shine in spring and early summer.</p>
            <p>For up-to-date regulations, visit the <a href="https://wdfw.wa.gov/">WDFW Website</a> or contact them at:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Email:</strong> info@wdfw.wa.gov</li>
                <li><strong>Phone:</strong> (360) 902-2200</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
